IAO:0000115: A tundra biome which exists at high altitudes and where vegetation - dominated by a few species of dwarf shrubs, a few grasses, sedges, lichens, and mosses - is stunted due to low temperatures and high winds.
rdfs:comment: The absence of trees in this biome is primarily due to high altitude rather than high latitude. On Earth, it lies roughly between the summer isotherm of 10 degrees Centigrade and the snow line. Primary productivity is low in this biome because of the extremes of climate.
rdfs:label: alpine tundra biome

IAO:0000115: The marine benthic biome (benthic meaning 'bottom') encompasses the seafloor and includes such areas as shores, littoral or intertidal areas, marine coral reefs, and the deep seabed.
rdfs:label: marine benthic biome

IAO:0000115: A biome which is determined by a freshwater lake.
rdfs:label: freshwater lake biome

IAO:0000115: A tundra ecosystem which is undergoing climactic ecological succession.
rdfs:label: tundra biome

IAO:0000115: The marine sponge reef biome comprises marine reefs primarily built by marine sponges. The primary frame-building sponges are all members of the order Hexactinosa. They are found only in glacier-scoured troughs of low-angle continental shelf. The seafloor is stable and consists of rock, coarse gravel, and large boulders.
rdfs:label: marine sponge reef biome

IAO:0000115: A forest ecosystem which is undergoing climactic ecological succession.
rdfs:label: forest biome

IAO:0000115: The marine neritic zone biome comprises sea floor from the high tide mark to a continental shelf break. This zone generally extends to 200 m below average sea level.
rdfs:label: marine neritic benthic zone biome

IAO:0000115: The abyssopelagic zone biome comprises the marine water column below the bathypelagic zone biome at approximately 2500 -2700 m and extends either to the hadal pelagic zone biome (at approximately 6000 m) or to the benthopelagic zone biome within ca. 100 m of the seafloor. The depth of 2700 m may be critical for physiological reasons as the change in hydrostatic pressure across this depth may preclude organism migration.
rdfs:label: oceanic abyssopelagic zone biome

IAO:0000115: A mediterranean sea biome which is subject to temperate climate patterns.
rdfs:label: temperate mediterranean sea biome

IAO:0000115: A marginal sea biome which is located in a region with a tropical climate.
IAO:0000116: A class which is complementary to the WWF Temperate Shelf and Seas ecoregions grouping
rdfs:label: tropical marginal sea biome

IAO:0000115: A rangeland biome is an anthropogenic terrestrial biome which is primarily used for the rearing and grazing of livestock.
rdfs:label: rangeland biome

IAO:0000115: The marine hydrothermal vent biome comprises regions of the marine benthic biome where heat generated due to tectonic activity, either at divergent plate boundaries or convergent ocean plates where back-arc spreading occurs, is released or 'vented' to the surface. The resultant high temperature water jets are laden with dissolved metals and minerals.
rdfs:label: marine hydrothermal vent biome

IAO:0000115: A marine black smoker biome comprises regions of the marine hydrothermal vent biome characterised by a black vent plume. This black plume is a consequence of dissolved metals and minerals forming complexes with sulphide and indicates polymetallic sulphide mineral deposits beneath the surface.
rdfs:label: marine black smoker biome

IAO:0000115: The oceanic mesopelagic zone biome comprises regions of the marine water column that occur offshore, beyond a continental shelf. This biome extends through the water column from approximately 200-1000 m depth - the maximal depth of light penetration in all but the clearest oligotrophic ocean regions. In comparison to the epipelagic zone, dominant forms of pelagic organisms do not change very much; however, there are marked changes in species composition and the proportion of smaller-sized individuals decreases.
rdfs:label: oceanic mesopelagic zone biome

IAO:0000115: A freshwater river biome which is determined by the delta of a large river.
rdfs:comment: "Large" is ambiguous. For details on "Large river deltas" (e.g. the Niger river delta) see http://worldwildlife.org/biomes/large-river-delta-ecosystems This class will be replaced with a less ambiguous class.
rdfs:label: large river delta biome

IAO:0000115: A polar desert biome is a desert biome which is subject to low levels of insolation, annual precipitation less than 250 millimeters, and a mean temperature less than 10 degrees Celsius during its warmest month. Temperature changes in polar deserts frequently cross the freezing point of water.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: polar desert biome

IAO:0000115: The marine hadal zone biome describes sea floor deeper than 6000 m such as that of the oceanic trenches.
rdfs:label: marine hadal zone biome

IAO:0000115: A subtropical broadleaf forest in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
rdfs:label: subtropical broadleaf forest biome

IAO:0000115: A biome is an ecosystem which is undergoing climactic ecological succession.
rdfs:comment: In this definition, there is an assumption that no major perturbations are occurring or have occurred in a time frame affects the successional dynamics of the ecosystem. A "major" perturbation is one which disrupts the community's ability to restore its (near) equilibrium. Usually, pioneer or early secondary successional processes would be in effect in such scenarios.
rdfs:label: biome

IAO:0000115: A biome which is  primarily or completely situated on a landmass.
rdfs:label: terrestrial biome

IAO:0000115: A woodland biome which is subject to tropical climate patterns.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: tropical woodland biome

IAO:0000115: A desert ecosystem which is undergoing climactic ecological succession.
rdfs:label: desert biome

IAO:0000115: A tropical moist broadleaf forest in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
rdfs:label: tropical moist broadleaf forest biome

IAO:0000115: A subtropical woodland biome which includes communities adapted to hot to warm, dry summers, mild to cold, rainy winters, and the influence of large, usually marine, bodies of water.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: mediterranean woodland biome

IAO:0000115: A village biome is an anthropogenic terrestrial biome which contains settlements such as villages, towns, and/or small cities and which is primarily used for agricultural activity.
rdfs:comment: Villages are also described as agricultural settlements with greater than 100 persons per square kilometre; however, no upper limit is defined.
rdfs:label: village biome

IAO:0000115: A broadleaf forest ecosystem which is undergoing climactic ecological succession.
rdfs:label: broadleaf forest biome

IAO:0000115: The bathypelagic zone biome comprises the marine water column below approximately 1000 m water depth - the maximum depth to which detectable daylight penetrates in all but the clearest oligotrophic waters - and extends to about 2500 - 2700 m water depth. In the temperate Atlantic, the beginning of the bathypelagic zone biome approximates to the deep oxygen minimum and the base of the permanent thermocline.
rdfs:label: oceanic bathypelagic zone biome

IAO:0000115: A freshwater river biome which is determined by a small river.
rdfs:comment: "Small" is ambiguous. For details on "Small rivers" (e.g. the Salween river) see http://worldwildlife.org/biomes/small-river-ecosystems. This class will be replaced with a less ambiguous class.
rdfs:label: small river biome

IAO:0000115: A woodland biome which is subject to subtropical climate patterns.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: subtropical woodland biome

IAO:0000115: A montane grassland biome is a grassland biome which occurs in regions elevated above sea level and which has community structure determined by elevation-dependent environmental conditions.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition.
rdfs:label: montane grassland biome

rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: tropical grassland biome

IAO:0000115: A temperate mixed forest in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
rdfs:label: temperate mixed forest biome

IAO:0000115: A biome which is subject to alpine altitudinal conditions.
dce:creator: orcid:0000-0002-4366-3088
rdfs:label: alpine biome

IAO:0000115: A marine ultramafic hydrothermal vent biome comprises regions of themarine  hydrothermal vent biome hosted on ultramafic (also referred to as ultrabasic) rocks. Ultramafic rocks are igneous and meta-igneous rocks with very low silica content (less than 45%), generally >18% MgO, high FeO, low potassium, and are composed of usually greater than 90% mafic minerals  (dark colored, high magnesium and iron content). The Earth's mantle is composed of ultramafic rocks.
rdfs:label: marine ultramafic hydrothermal vent biome

IAO:0000115: A subtropical grassland biome which includes communities adapted to hot to warm, dry summers, mild to cold, rainy winters, and the influence of large, usually marine, bodies of water.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: mediterranean grassland biome

IAO:0000115: A savanna biome which is subject to mediterranean climate patterns.
rdfs:label: mediterranean savanna biome

IAO:0000115: A montane desert biome is a desert biome which occurs in regions elevated above sea level and which has community structure determined by elevation-dependent environmental conditions.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition.
rdfs:label: montane desert biome

IAO:0000115: A shrubland biome which is subject to temperate climate patterns.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: temperate shrubland biome

IAO:0000115: The marine pelagic biome (pelagic meaning open sea) is that of the marine water column, from the surface to the greatest depths.
rdfs:label: marine pelagic biome

IAO:0000115: Expressions of the estuarine biome occur at wide lower courses of a rivers where they flow into a sea. Estuaries experience tidal flows and their water is a changing mixture of fresh and salt.
rdfs:label: estuarine biome

IAO:0000115: A mangrove biome is a terrestrial biome which includes, across its spatial extent, mangrove plants (Rhizophoraceae). Mangrove plants are able to withstand high levels of salinity as well as regions of anoxia and frequent tidal inundation. Mangrove biomes often occur near tropical and sub-tropical estuaries and depositional marine coastal environments where fine sediments (often with high organic content) collect in areas protected from high energy wave action.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. Depending on whether mangrove trees or shrubs are present, this class could be a child of shrubland biome or woodland biome. Consider creating the appropriate classes.
rdfs:label: mangrove biome

IAO:0000115: A biome which has little permanent surface water and a low relative abundance of springs.
IAO:0000116: The WWF definition is somewhat ambiguous, but workable.
rdfs:label: xeric basin biome

IAO:0000115: A freshwater biome which is determined by a freshwater river.
rdfs:label: freshwater river biome

IAO:0000115: An anthropogenic terrestrial biome is a terrestrial biome which has community structures determined by human activity.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition.
rdfs:label: anthropogenic terrestrial biome

IAO:0000115: A biome which is subject to polar climatic conditions.
rdfs:comment: This class is primarily for inference and, in general, should not be used directly by annotators. If you're an annotator, please consider using a more informative term such as 'tundra biome'.
rdfs:label: polar biome

IAO:0000115: The oceanic sea surface microlayer (SML) biome comprises the top 1000 micrometers of the marine surface waters occurring offshore, away from a continental shelf. It is the boundary layer where all exchange occurs between the atmosphere and the ocean. The chemical, physical, and biological properties of the SML differ greatly from the sub-surface water just a few centimeters beneath.
rdfs:label: oceanic sea surface microlayer biome

rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: xeric shrubland biome

IAO:0000115: The neritic epipelagic zone biome comprises the marine water column above a continental shelf.
rdfs:label: neritic pelagic zone biome

IAO:0000115: An urban biome is a dense settlement biome which has been urbanised.
rdfs:label: urban biome

IAO:0000115: A biome which is determined by a water body and which has ecological climax communities adapted to life in or on water.
rdfs:label: aquatic biome

IAO:0000115: A grassland ecosystem in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
rdfs:label: grassland biome

IAO:0000115: A coniferous forest biome which is subject to tropical climate patterns.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: tropical coniferous forest biome

IAO:0000115: A marine white smoker biome comprises regions of the marine hydrothermal vent biome characterised by lightly hued plumes, typically containing barium, calcium, and silicon. These vents tend to have lower temperature plumes when compared to black smoker environments.
rdfs:label: marine white smoker biome

IAO:0000115: The oceanic hadal pelagic zone biome comprises the water column in oceanic trenches occurring at depths between 6000m and 10,000m.
rdfs:label: oceanic hadal pelagic zone biome

IAO:0000115: A freshwater stream ecosystem which is undergoing climactic ecological succession.
dce:creator: orcid:0000-0001-9076-6066
rdfs:label: freshwater stream biome

IAO:0000115: A mixed forest in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
rdfs:label: mixed forest biome

IAO:0000115: The marine salt marsh biome comprises marshes that are transitional intertidals between land and salty or brackish marine water (e.g.: sloughs, bays, estuaries). It is dominated by halophytic (salt tolerant) herbaceous plants. The daily tidal surges bring in nutrients, which tend to settle in roots of the plants within the salt marsh. The natural chemical activity of salty (or brackish) water and the tendency of algae to bloom in the shallow unshaded water also allow for great biodiversity.
rdfs:label: marine salt marsh biome

IAO:0000115: The concentration basin mediterranean sea biome comprises expressions of the mediterranean sea biome that have higher salinity than bordering oceans due to evaporation. Water exchange consists of inflow of the fresher oceanic water in the upper layer and outflow of the saltier mediterranean water in the lower layer of the connecting channel.
rdfs:label: concentration basin mediterranean sea biome

IAO:0000115: The marine abyssal zone biome comprises regions of the marine benthic biome  between approximately 2500 m and 6000 m depth. This zone generally coincides with the continental rise and the abyssal plain.
rdfs:label: marine abyssal zone biome

IAO:0000115: A biome which is subject to tropical climatic conditions.
dce:creator: orcid:0000-0002-4366-3088
rdfs:label: tropical biome

rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: temperate grassland biome

IAO:0000115: The mediterranean sea biome comprises mostly enclosed seas that have limited exchange of deep water with outer oceans and where the water circulation is dominated by salinity and temperature differences rather than winds.
rdfs:label: mediterranean sea biome

IAO:0000115: A marginal sea biome which is located in a region with a temperate climate.
IAO:0000116: A component of the WWF Temperate Shelf and seas ecoregions grouping
rdfs:label: temperate marginal sea biome

IAO:0000115: A shrubland biome which is subject to subtropical climate patterns.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: subtropical shrubland biome

IAO:0000115: A montane savanna biome is a savanna biome which occurs in regions elevated above sea level and which has community structure determined by elevation-dependent environmental conditions.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition.
rdfs:label: montane savanna biome

IAO:0000115: A subtropical desert biome is a desert biome which has communities adapted to temperatures above a monthly average of 18 degrees Celsius, high daily temperature ranges of approximately 20 degrees Celsius, high insolation (but lower than that of a tropical desert biome), inhibited cloud formation, and very low precipitation. Subtropical desert biomes located near coasts with cold upwellings may have cooler temperatures and reduced insolution due to fog.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: subtropical desert biome

IAO:0000115: A biome which is subject to subapline altitudinal conditions.
dce:creator: orcid:0000-0002-4366-3088
rdfs:label: subalpine biome

IAO:0000115: A temperate desert biome is a desert biome which has communities adapted to intermediate insolation, low rainfall, and large temperature variations between winter and summer. Winter temperatures may fall below 0 degrees Celsius. Some precipitation in this biome may fall as snow.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: temperate desert biome

IAO:0000115: The benthopelagic zone biome comprises regions of the marine water column which usually coincide with the benthic boundary layer (BBL) - the layer of isothermal and isohaline water contiguous to the sea floor. A general reversal in the declining gradient of pelagic biomass may be observed here, perhaps explained by viable nutrition on the sea floor being resuspended by bottom currents. This zone typically extends 100 m above the seafloor, but may reach upto1000 m during benthic storms.
rdfs:label: oceanic benthopelagic zone biome

IAO:0000115: A subtropical grassland in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
rdfs:label: subtropical grassland biome

IAO:0000115: A coniferous forest biome which is subject to subtropical climate patterns.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: subtropical coniferous forest biome

IAO:0000115: A woodland biome which is subject to temperate climate patterns.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: temperate woodland biome

IAO:0000115: A tropical mixed forest in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
dce:creator: orcid:0000-0002-4366-3088
rdfs:label: tropical mixed forest biome

IAO:0000115: A tropical desert biome is a desert biome which has communities adapted to temperatures above a monthly average of 18 degrees Celsius, high daily temperature ranges of approximately 20 degrees Celsius, very high insolation due to inhibited cloud formation, and very low precipitation. Tropical desert biomes located near coasts with cold upwellings may have cooler temperatures and reduced insolution due to fog.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: tropical desert biome

IAO:0000115: A subtropical dry broadleaf forest in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
rdfs:label: subtropical dry broadleaf forest biome

IAO:0000115: A woodland biome is a terrestrial biome which includes, across its entire spatial extent, woody plants spaced sufficiently far apart to allow light penetration to support communities of herbaceous plants or shrubs living closer to the woodland floor.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition.
rdfs:label: woodland biome

IAO:0000115: The oceanic epipelagic zone biome comprises regions of the marine water column that occur offshore, beyond a continental shelf. This biome extends from the surface of the ocean to a depth of ca. 200-250m. Throughout the zone the light field tends to be asymmetrical vertically, so that the direction and elevation of the sun can still be detected. The oceanic epipelagic zone biome encompasses the euphotic zone and, where and when it occurs, the seasonal thermocline.
rdfs:label: oceanic epipelagic zone biome

IAO:0000115: A tropical broadleaf forest in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
rdfs:label: tropical broadleaf forest biome

IAO:0000115: A marine upwelling biome which is located in a region subject to temperate climate patterns.
rdfs:label: temperate marine upwelling biome

IAO:0000115: A cropland ecosystem which is undergoing climactic ecological succession.
rdfs:label: cropland biome

IAO:0000115: A flooded savanna biome is a savanna biome which has very wet to saturated soil moisture content.
rdfs:label: flooded savanna biome

IAO:0000115: A marine coral reef biome which is located in a region with a tropical climate.
rdfs:label: tropical marine coral reef biome

IAO:0000115: A biome which is subject to subpolar climatic conditions.
dce:creator: orcid:0000-0002-4366-3088
rdfs:label: subpolar biome

IAO:0000115: The neritic sea surface microlayer (SML) biome comprises the top 1000 micrometers of marine surface waters occurring above a continental shelf. It is the boundary layer where all exchange occurs between the atmosphere and the ocean. The chemical, physical, and biological properties of the SML differ greatly from the sub-surface water just a few centimeters beneath.
rdfs:label: neritic sea surface microlayer biome

IAO:0000115: A biome which is subject to arid environmental conditions.
dce:creator: orcid:0000-0002-4366-3088
rdfs:label: arid biome

IAO:0000115: A montane shrubland biome is a shrubland biome which occurs in regions elevated above sea level and which has community structure determined by elevation-dependent environmental conditions.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition.
rdfs:label: montane shrubland biome

IAO:0000115: A woodland biome which has seasonal water availability and includes trees spaced sufficiently far apart to allow an unbroken layer of grass, sedge (Cyperaceae) or  rush (Juncaceae) communities to live.
rdfs:label: savanna biome

IAO:0000115: A savanna biome which is subject to temperate climate patterns.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: temperate savanna biome

IAO:0000115: A coniferous forest biome which is subject to temperate climate patterns.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: temperate coniferous forest biome

IAO:0000115: A shrubland biome which is densely vegetated by dwarf or short mangroves (and associates) that are generally less than 6 meters in height, is tidally influenced,  is located in tropical or subtropical areas.
rdfs:comment: This class aligns to the Coastal and Marine Ecological Classification Standard (CMECS). In ENVO, we may adapt the definition for consistency, but the semantics (meaning) of the term should be unaffected. Please consult the CMECS catalogue (https://cmecscatalog.org/) for authoritative and semantically unconstrained definitions. CMECS provides the following notes: "Commonly found on intertidal mud flats along the shores of estuaries. Tidal mangrove shrublands may include immature stands or stunted mature trees that indicate a harsh growing environment. Areas characterized by tall mangroves (> 6 meters) are placed in the Tidal Mangrove Forest Biotic Group. Where tidal amplitude is relatively low, the vegetation forms narrow bands along the coastal plains, and it rarely penetrates inland more than several kilometers along rivers. Where tidal amplitude is greater, mangroves extend further inland along river courses, forming extensive stands in the major river deltas. Also, mangrove cays may occur within the lagoon complex of barrier reefs. The list of biotic communities for this group is long: a few examples are provided below, and the complete list is available in Appendix F"
rdfs:label: tidal mangrove shrubland

IAO:0000115: A coniferous forest biome is a forest biome which contains densely packed populations or communities of coniferous trees, strongly limiting light penetration to the forest floor.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition.
rdfs:label: coniferous forest biome

IAO:0000115: A freshwater biome which is determined by a large lake.
rdfs:comment: "Large" is ambiguous. For details on "Large lakes" (e.g. African rift lakes) see http://worldwildlife.org/biomes/large-lake-ecosystems This class will be replaced with a less ambiguous class.
rdfs:label: large freshwater lake biome

IAO:0000115: A marine biome which is determined by an ocean.
rdfs:comment: Ocean biomes are determined by major bodies of saline water, principal components of the hydrosphere. Approximately 71% of the Earth's surface is covered by ocean, a continuous body of water that is customarily divided into several principal oceans and smaller seas. More than half of this area is over 3,000 metres (9,800 ft) deep. Average oceanic salinity is around 35 parts per thousand (ppt) (3.5%), and nearly all seawater has a salinity in the range of 30 to 38 ppt.
rdfs:label: ocean biome

IAO:0000115: A biome which is subject to subtropical climatic conditions.
dce:creator: orcid:0000-0002-4366-3088
rdfs:label: subtropical biome

IAO:0000115: A marine upwelling biome which is subject to tropical climate patterns.
rdfs:label: tropical marine upwelling biome

IAO:0000115: A marine benthic biome which is determined by a cold seep.
rdfs:comment: The marine cold seep biome comprises regions of the marine benthic biome where seepage of methane, hydrogen sulphide, hydrocarbon rich fluids and other fluids occurs.
rdfs:label: marine cold seep biome

IAO:0000115: A marine basaltic hydrothermal vent biome comprises regions of the marine hydrothermal vent biome hosted on basaltic rocks. Basalt generally has a composition of 45 to 55 wt % SiO2, 2 to 6 wt % total alkalis, 0.5 to 2.0 wt % TiO2, 5 to 14 wt % FeO and 14 wt % or more Al2O3. Contents of CaO are commonly near 10 wt %, those of MgO commonly in the range 5 to 12 wt %.
rdfs:label: marine basaltic hydrothermal vent biome

IAO:0000115: The marginal sea biome comprises parts of an ocean partially enclosed by land such as islands, archipelagos, or peninsulas. Unlike mediterranean seas, marginal seas have ocean currents caused by ocean winds. Many marginal seas are enclosed by island arcs that were formed from the subduction of one oceanic plate beneath another.
rdfs:label: marginal sea biome

IAO:0000115: The dilution basin mediterranean sea biome comprises expressions of the mediterranean sea biome with lower salinity than the surrounding ocean due to freshwater gains such as rainfall and rivers. Water exchange consists of outflow of the fresher mediterranean water in the upper layer and inflow of the saltier oceanic water in the lower layer of the channel. Renewal of deep water may not be sufficient to supply oxygen to the bottom.
rdfs:label: dilution basin mediterranean sea biome

IAO:0000115: A shrubland biome is a terrestrial biome which includes, across its entire spatial extent, dense groups of shrubs.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition.
rdfs:label: shrubland biome

IAO:0000115: A savanna biome which is subject to subtropical climate patterns.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: subtropical savanna biome

IAO:0000115: A freshwater lake biome which is determined by a small lake.
rdfs:comment: "Small" is ambiguous. For details on "Small lakes" (e.g. Cameroon crater lakes)  see http://worldwildlife.org/biomes/small-lake-ecosystems. This class will be replaced with a less ambiguous class.
rdfs:label: small freshwater lake biome

IAO:0000115: The marine bathyal zone biome comprises regions of the marine benthic biome between approximately 200 m and 3000 m depth. This zone generally coincides with the continental slope.
rdfs:label: marine bathyal zone biome

IAO:0000115: A subtropical moist broadleaf forest in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
rdfs:label: subtropical moist broadleaf forest biome

IAO:0000115: The marine rocky subtidal reef biome comprises regions of the marine reef biome composed mainly of rock and which harbour abundant communities of algae and invertebrates. These reefs are often very patchy, with alterations of rocks dominated by rich invertebrate assemblages and turf-forming calcareous red algae.
rdfs:label: marine subtidal rocky reef biome

IAO:0000115: A biome which is subject to temperate climatic conditions.
dce:creator: orcid:0000-0002-4366-3088
rdfs:label: temperate biome

IAO:0000115: An aquatic biome which is determined by a body of freshwater.
rdfs:label: freshwater biome

IAO:0000115: A shrubland biome which is subject to tropical climate patterns.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: tropical shrubland biome

IAO:0000115: A freshwater river biome which is determined by the headwaters of a large river.
rdfs:comment: "Large" is ambiguous. For details on "Large river headwaters" (e.g. the Upper Amazon headwaters) see http://worldwildlife.org/biomes/large-river-headwater-ecosystems This class will be replaced with a less ambiguous class.
rdfs:label: large river headwater biome

IAO:0000115: The oceanic epipelagic zone biome comprises the marine water column offshore, beyond a continental shelf.
rdfs:label: oceanic pelagic zone biome

IAO:0000115: A dense settlement biome is an anthropogenic terrestrial biome which is primarily used for human habitation, recreation, and industry within built structures with little other land use.
rdfs:label: dense settlement biome

IAO:0000115: A broadleaf forest which is subject to temperate climate patterns.
rdfs:label: temperate broadleaf forest biome

IAO:0000115: A biome expressed by strips or ridges of rocks, sand, or coral that rises to or near the surface of a body of marine water.
rdfs:label: marine reef biome

IAO:0000115: A mediterranean shrubland biome is a subtropical shrubland biome which includes communities adapted to hot to warm, dry summers, mild to cold, rainy winters, and the influence of large, usually marine, bodies of water.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: mediterranean shrubland biome

IAO:0000115: A freshwater river biome which is determined by a large river.
rdfs:comment: "Large" is ambiguous. For details on "Large rivers" (e.g. the Mekong river) see http://worldwildlife.org/biomes/large-river-ecosystems This class will be replaced with a less ambiguous class.
rdfs:label: large river biome

IAO:0000115: A mediterranean forest in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
rdfs:label: mediterranean forest biome

IAO:0000115: The neritic mesopelagic zone biome comprises the marine column that occurs above a continental shelf and extends from approximately 200 to 1000 m depth - the maximal depth of light penetration in all but the clearest oligotrophic ocean regions. In comparison to the epipelagic zone, dominant forms of pelagic organisms do not change very much; however, there are marked changes in species composition and the proportion of smaller-sized individuals decreases.
rdfs:label: neritic mesopelagic zone biome

IAO:0000115: A biome which is subject to montane altitudinal conditions.
dce:creator: orcid:0000-0002-4366-3088
rdfs:label: montane biome

IAO:0000115: A tropical dry broadleaf forest in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
rdfs:label: tropical dry broadleaf forest biome

IAO:0000115: A biome which is subject to mediterranean climatic conditions.
dce:creator: orcid:0000-0002-4366-3088
rdfs:label: mediterranean biome

IAO:0000115: A  coniferous forest biome which includes communities adapted to subpolar conditions.
rdfs:label: subpolar coniferous forest biome

IAO:0000115: An aquatic biome which is determined by a marine water body.
rdfs:comment: This biome includes open-ocean and unprotected coastal ecosystems, characterized by exposure to wave action, tidal fluctuation, and ocean currents as well as systems that largely resemble these. Water in the marine biome is generally within the salinity range of seawater: 30 to 38 ppt.
rdfs:label: marine biome

IAO:0000115: A marine biome which contains communities adapted to living in an environment determined by an upwelling process.
rdfs:label: marine upwelling biome

IAO:0000115: A savanna biome which is subject to tropical climate patterns.
rdfs:comment: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
rdfs:label: tropical savanna biome

IAO:0000115: The neritic epipelagic zone biome comprises the marine water column that occurs above a continental shelf and extends from the surface of the ocean to a depth of ca. 200-250m. Throughout the zone the light field tends to be asymmetrical vertically, so that the direction and elevation of the sun can still be detected. The epipelagic zone encompasses the euphotic zone and, where and when it occurs, the seasonal thermocline.
rdfs:label: neritic epipelagic zone biome

IAO:0000115: The epeiric sea (also known as an epicontinental sea) biome comprises a shallow seas that extend over part of a continent. Epeiric seas are usually associated with the marine transgressions of the geologic  past, which have variously been due to either global eustatic sea level changes, local tectonic deformation, or both, and are occasionally semi-cyclic.
rdfs:label: epeiric sea biome

IAO:0000115: The marine coral reef biome comprises constructional wave-resistant entities which are primarily built by corals and are often cemented together. The growth of these structures is aided by zooxanthellae, algae that are symbiotic with the reef-building corals.
rdfs:label: marine coral reef biome
